NEXUS: "Engineer, the cascade failure revealed weaknesses in our network design.
       Your mission is to understand network segmentation - dividing infrastructure
       into security zones based on trust levels. This is how station architects
       design secure systems. Learn the three-tier model, then apply it."

━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━

OBJECTIVE
═════════
Network segmentation divides infrastructure into zones:
  - DMZ (Demilitarized Zone): Public-facing services
  - Application Tier: Business logic, API servers
  - Data Tier: Databases, storage, caches

Each tier has different security requirements and access patterns.
Containers only receive access to tiers they need.

━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━

CURRENT ARCHITECTURE
════════════════════

Internet
    |
    v
┌─────────────────────────────┐
│   Frontend Zone (DMZ)       │
│   172.20.0.0/24             │
│   - client (user access)    │
│   - server (web)            │
│   - api (gateway)           │
└──────────────┬──────────────┘
               │
        [API Gateway]
               │
┌──────────────┴──────────────┐
│   Backend Zone              │
│   172.21.0.0/24             │
│   - api (internal)          │
│   - database                │
│   - monitor (admin)         │
└─────────────────────────────┘

━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━

TASKS
═════

[ ] Task 1: Analyze Current Two-Tier Setup
    docker network inspect network-lab_frontend_net --format '
    Subnet: {{range .IPAM.Config}}{{.Subnet}}{{end}}
    Gateway: {{range .IPAM.Config}}{{.Gateway}}{{end}}
    Containers: {{range .Containers}}{{.Name}} {{end}}'

    docker network inspect network-lab_backend_net --format '
    Subnet: {{range .IPAM.Config}}{{.Subnet}}{{end}}
    Gateway: {{range .IPAM.Config}}{{.Gateway}}{{end}}
    Containers: {{range .Containers}}{{.Name}} {{end}}'

[ ] Task 2: Design Three-Tier Access Rules
    Consider what traffic should be allowed:

    | From | To   | Allow? | Reason                    |
    |------|------|--------|---------------------------|
    | DMZ  | App  | Yes    | Forward user requests     |
    | DMZ  | Data | No     | No direct DB access       |
    | App  | Data | Yes    | Query databases           |
    | App  | DMZ  | Yes    | Return responses          |
    | Data | *    | No     | Data never initiates      |
    | Mgmt | All  | Yes    | Admins need full access   |

[ ] Task 3: Build a Three-Tier Test Environment
    # Create networks
    docker network create --subnet=172.50.0.0/24 tier-dmz
    docker network create --subnet=172.51.0.0/24 tier-app
    docker network create --subnet=172.52.0.0/24 tier-data

    # DMZ tier - web server
    docker run -d --name web --network tier-dmz nginx:alpine

    # App tier - connects to DMZ and Data
    docker run -d --name app --network tier-app nicolaka/netshoot sleep 3600
    docker network connect tier-dmz app
    docker network connect tier-data app

    # Data tier - database
    docker run -d --name db --network tier-data \
      --env POSTGRES_PASSWORD=test postgres:15-alpine

[ ] Task 4: Verify Tier Isolation
    # Web can only see DMZ
    docker exec web ping -c 1 172.51.0.2 2>&1 || echo "Web cannot reach app tier"
    docker exec web ping -c 1 172.52.0.2 2>&1 || echo "Web cannot reach data tier"

    # App can reach all tiers (connected to all)
    docker exec app ping -c 1 172.50.0.2  # web in DMZ
    docker exec app ping -c 1 172.52.0.2  # db in data tier

    # DB is isolated
    docker exec db sh -c "ping -c 1 172.50.0.2 2>&1" || echo "DB cannot reach DMZ"

[ ] Task 5: Document the Architecture
    For any segmented network, document:
    1. Network map (subnets, gateways)
    2. Traffic flows (what talks to what)
    3. Access rules (allowed/denied)
    4. Gateway services (what bridges zones)
    5. Monitoring points (where to inspect)

[ ] Task 6: Cleanup Test Environment
    docker rm -f web app db 2>/dev/null
    docker network rm tier-dmz tier-app tier-data 2>/dev/null

━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━

SEGMENTATION BEST PRACTICES
═══════════════════════════
  1. Minimize cross-zone traffic (smaller attack surface)
  2. Use gateway services (don't expose databases directly)
  3. Implement least privilege (only needed connections)
  4. Monitor zone boundaries (log cross-zone traffic)
  5. Separate management (admin access on dedicated network)

SECURITY CONTROLS PER TIER:
  DMZ:  Rate limiting, WAF, DDoS protection, TLS termination
  App:  Auth/authz, input validation, secrets management
  Data: Encryption at rest, minimal ports, no external access

━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━

VERIFICATION
════════════
Run: ./verify

Success: You understand three-tier architecture, can design network
segmentation, and know what traffic to allow between tiers.

